Analysis of Longevity

Ryan Abdella

January 15, 2015

This document will walk through the process of analyzing the results of wMicrotracker data on longevity of C. elegans.

source("~/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability/wMT_fxns.R")
library("dplyr")

wd <- "~/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability/"

Now lets import the data from the wMicrotracker reports. The function is able to pull all information about bin size, length of experiment and number of groups out of the file.

replicates <- 8
nstrains <- 12
data_points_per_day <- 4
plateID <- "Longevity_1_2"

files.trial1 <- dir(path = wd, plateID, full.names = T)
df.trial1 <- ldply(files.trial1, processMicrotrackerReport) %>% filter(time < 9)
## [1] "/Users/ryan/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability//20150123_Longevity_1_2mgmL.txt"
## [1] "/Users/ryan/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability//20150124_Longevity_1_2mgmL.txt"
## [1] "/Users/ryan/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability//20150125_Longevity_1_2mgmL.txt"
## [1] "/Users/ryan/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability//20150126_Longevity_1_2mgmL.txt"
## [1] "/Users/ryan/Dropbox/Ryan/Longevity Heritability//20150127_Longevity_1_2mgmL.txt"
df.trial1$day <- rep(1:(length(files.trial1)), each = nstrains * replicates * data_points_per_day)

Lets take a look at the activity data from the individual wells first.

ggplot(df.trial1) + aes(x=day, y=activity) + geom_point() + facet_grid(row~col) +
  labs(x="Time (day)", y="Activity", title = "Longevity #1")

Next we will combine the two time points for each day.

combined.trial1 <- aggregate(activity ~ row + col + day, data = df.trial1, sum)

Next we will add the strain information.

combined.trial1 <- combined.trial1[order(combined.trial1$col, combined.trial1$row, combined.trial1$day), ]
df.trial1 <- df.trial1[order(df.trial1$col, df.trial1$row, df.trial1$day), ]

strains <- c("CB4856", "CX11314", "ED3017", "JT11398", "DL238", "N2", "MY23", "JU258", "EG4725",  "LKC34", "JU775", "MY16")

combined.trial1$strain <- rep(strains, each = replicates * length(files.trial1))
df.trial1$strain <- rep(strains, each = replicates * length(files.trial1) * data_points_per_day)

Lets remove contaminated columns and missing worms

combined.trial1$activity[(combined.trial1$col %in% 2)] <- NA
df.trial1$activity[(df.trial1$col %in% 2)] <- NA

Lets normalize the data to % survival

combined.trial1 <- combined.trial1 %>%
  group_by(col, row) %>%
  mutate(norm.act = 100 * activity / max(activity, na.rm = T))

df.trial1 <- df.trial1 %>%
  group_by(col, row) %>%
  mutate(norm.act = 100 * activity / max(activity, na.rm = T))

ggplot(df.trial1) + aes(x=day, y=norm.act) + ylim(0, 100) + geom_point() + facet_grid(row~col)

Now lets fit some lines to the data to determine the best fit.

gompertz <- function(input, df, name) {
  sum(((100*100^((input[1]/input[2])*(1-exp(input[2]*df$day[df$strain == name]))))-df$norm.act[df$strain == name])^2)
}

weibull <- function(input, df, name) {
  sum(((100*100^(-((df$day[df$strain == name]/input[2])^input[1])))-df$norm.act[df$strain == name])^2)
}

twoplog <- function(input, df, row, col) {
  sum(((100/(1 + ((df$day[df$row == row & df$col == col]/input[2])^input[1])))-df$norm.act[df$row == row & df$col == col])^2)
}

threeplog <- function(input, df, name) {
  sum(((100*100^(-input[2]*df$day[df$strain == name] - (input[2]/input[3])*ln((input[1] - (input[2] - input[1])*exp(-input[3]*df$day[df$strain == name]))/input[2])))-df$norm.act[df$strain == name])^2)
}
